REMOVE FIRSTCASHPRICE

1. Analysis

  1. The problem

A used vehicle marketplace in Denmark wants to automate the valuation of the used vehicles sold in their platform.

Vehicle dealers have to estimate the price of the used vehicles they sell on the digital marketplace.

The company owning this marketplace wants to offer automated vehicle valuation as a service to these customers.

  1. Define the objective in business terms

The objective of the company is to provide predictions of vehicle prices to their customer, so that they do not have to make these predictions manually.

They would be satisfied with an error in the prediction that is not higher 20 % of the lower bound of the interquartile range of used vehicle prices.

  1. How should you frame the problem (supervised/unsupervised etc.)?

As we are trying to predict a continuous value for the price and we have a label for the past used vehicle prices, we will frame the problem as a supervised regression problem.

  1. How should performance be measured?

Performance will be measured using RMSE, which will give us a good indication of the error in DKK.

$R^2$ will also be used to have an indication of the variance explain by the model.

2. Get the data

The data used in this project is real data from the company's market place. They provided us with a data extract for a certain period of time. The data is confidential and must not be shared with other parties or used for other purposes than this course's project.

However, we rather have as many instances as we can, instead creating a more even distribution.

From the columns we previously displayed, the following are dates that are not relevant to predict the price.

We assume they are not relevant becasue some are used to calculate DAYSTOSOLD, and others mainly give information about updates in the system.

  • PERIOD_START_DATE: Date on which a vehicle was added to the listing as on sale.

  • PERIOD_END_DATE: Date on which a vehicle was removed from the listing.

  • EVENTDATETIME: Updates in the system corresponding to any kind of change in the vehicle details.

  • FIRST_PUBLICATION_DATE: Date on which a vehicle was added to the listing.

  • DELETEDDATE: Date on which a vehicle was removed completely from the listing.

  • MONTHNAME_FIRST_PUBLICATION_DATE: Month in which the vehicle was published first.

  • ROW_NUMBER_MULTIPLE_UPDATES_WITHIN_SAME_DAY: Count of times a vehicle was updated in one day.

  • DAYSTOSOLD_USING_LIVE_DAYS: Days it took for a vehicle to be sold while it was listed.

  • PRICE_CHANGE_FLAG: If the price was changed.

We are interested in the final price the vehicle was sold for, so we only use the final sale price.

The definitions for the other features are:

  • LISTINGTYPE: The listing of a vehicle can be Standard, Plus, or Discount, depending on the choice of the user.
  • DAYSTOSOLD: The days it took for a vehicle to sell.
  • SOLD: True if the vehicle was sold, false if not.
  • OBJECT_ID: the id of the vehicle in the system.
  • CashPrice: Our label. The current price of the car, or the price the car was finally sold for.
  • Mileage: Amount of kms travelled by the vehicle.
  • FIRST_AD_TYPE: First type of advertisement chosen. There are three types.
  • AD_TYPE: Advertisement type when sold.
  • PROFESSIONAL_USER_ID: Id of the user.
  • FUEL_TYPE: Type of fuel used by the vehicle.
  • AgeInMonths: Age of the car in months.
  • POSTALCODE: The postal code of the car dealer.
  • driveWheels: Front, back or 4.
  • ChassisTypeOne: Type of chassis. It includes many types.
  • effect: Horse power.
  • gearType: Manual or automatic.
  • model: The model of the vehicle.
  • modelYear: The year of the vehicle's model.
  • trimStyle: Different versions of a model.
  • modelSeries: The series of the model.
  • priceFromNew: Market price of a new vehicle.
  • acceleration0To100: Acceletation from 0 to 100.
  • engineType: Type of engine. There are for options.
  • height: The height of the vehicle.
  • length: The length of the vehicle.
  • numberOfDoors: The number of doors of the vehicle.
  • payload: The load that the vehicle can carry.
  • topSpeed: The vehicle's top speed.
  • totalWeight: The weight of the vehicle including passengers and cargo.
  • weight: The weight of the vehicle.
  • width: The width of the vehicle.
  • make: The vehicle's make (VW, Peugeot, ...)

We will now remove some outliers. For the prices we want to remove as least as possible, so we will not multiple the interquartile range by 2/3.

We also remove the negative values for AgeInMonths, keep other outliers.

In[]:
for num_feature in ["priceFromNew", "CashPrice"]:
    q25, q75 = df[num_feature].quantile(0.25), df[num_feature].quantile(0.75)

    iqr = q75 - q25
    cut_off = iqr
    lower, upper = 0, q75 + cut_off
    if df[num_feature].isnull().sum() > 0:
        print(f"Ignored {num_feature}")
    else:
        print(f"{num_feature} has a lower = {lower} and a upper = {upper}")
        df = df.drop(df[df[num_feature] > upper].index)
        df = df.drop(df[df[num_feature] < lower].index)

df = df[df["AgeInMonths"] >= 0]

# This function allows us to select columns and distinguish between num and cat for both the sample and entire data later on.
def num_and_cat_dfs(df, num_features, cat_features):
    df_num = df[num_features]
    df_cat = df[cat_features]
    return df_num, df_cat
In[]:
df_num_sample, df_cat_sample = num_and_cat_dfs(df_sample, num_features, cat_features)

We now take out the label from the numerical features.

In[]:
# This function allows us to separate the label from the features for both the sample and the entire data later on.
def label_and_num_features(label, df_num):
    y = df_num[label]
    X_num = df_num[df_num.columns[1:]]
    return y, X_num
In[]:
y_sample, X_num_sample = label_and_num_features("CashPrice", df_num_sample)

Next, we want to impute the null data from our numerical features. We will use the SimpleImputer, and use the median. (We used other imputers, but there was not a big difference in the final results.)

We also scale the data.

In[]:
def impute_and_scale(X_num):
    missing_columns = X_num.columns
    imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy="median")
    features_imputed = imputer.fit_transform(X_num)
    imputed_data = pd.DataFrame(features_imputed, columns=missing_columns)
    std_scale = StandardScaler(copy=True)
    features_scaled = std_scale.fit_transform(imputed_data)
    return pd.DataFrame(features_scaled, columns=missing_columns)
In[]:
scaled_sample_data = impute_and_scale(X_num_sample)

The categorical features have to be encoded, and for this we use OneHotEncoder.

5. Short-list promising models

As we are trying to predict a continuous value, the price in DKK, so we will use a regression model.

We will first try out the following models with their default parameters and without cross validation:

  • Linear Regression
  • Decision Tree Regressor
  • Random Forest Regressor
  • KNeighbors Regressor
  • SVM
  • GradientBoosting Regressor
  • Neural Network

We will fit these models using the sample we generated previously of 10000 rows. We know this is not ideal, but it is a way of fitting the models faster, and it should at least give us an indication of what models performe best.

We will validate the training results against the test results to see what models perform best, using RMSE and $R^2$.

In[]:
def display_preliminary_scores(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    predict_train = model.predict(X_train)
    predict_test = model.predict(X_test)
    print(f"Train RMSE score: {np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, predict_train))}")
    print(f"Train R2 score: {r2_score(y_train,predict_train)*100}")
    print(f"Test RMSE score: {np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, predict_test))}")
    print(f"Test R2 score: {r2_score(y_test,predict_test)*100}")

We create a simple neural network with an input and an output layer. We will have the same number of units as features in the data and the input shape will be the length of the sample.

We will use MSE for the model and the Adam optimizer. The only callback we will include is EarlyStopping.

In[]:
def build_model():
    model = keras.Sequential([
        Dense(X_train_sample.shape[1], activation='relu', input_shape=[len(X_train_sample[0])]),
        Dense(1)
    ])

    model.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(), 
                  loss='mse',
                  metrics='mse')
    return model

model = build_model()    

my_callbacks = [
tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(patience=10, restore_best_weights=True),]

history = model.fit(X_train_sample, y_train_sample, epochs = 40, validation_split = 0.2, callbacks=[my_callbacks])

We will now select three models based on the results.

Clearly, the SVM and the Linear Regression models are missing the mark by far. So we will not move forward with these.

The Decision Tree is not performing that bad, but it is overfitting quite a lot. So we discard it.

The Random Forest is performing better, but it is also overfitting, although not as mush as the Decision Tree. It achieves better scores than the Gradient Boosting Regressor and takes around the same time to fit, although the Gradient Boosting is overfitting less. But if we can reduce overfitting, the Random Forest looks more promising. Therefore, we will pick the Random Forest, and drop Gradient Boosting.

Kneigbors does not achieve better test scores than the Gradient Boosting Regressor, or the Random Forest, but it is fast and can easily tuned. Therefore, we will give it a chance to shine.

Finally, the neural network takes the longest time and it is overfitting. But the results in the graph look promising, it has a different approach to the rest of the models, and there are many possible ways of tuninig it. So we will keep working on it.

In summary, we select:

  • Random Forest Regressor
  • Kneighbors Regressor
  • Neural Network

forest_imp = forest_reg.feature_importances_
In[]:
def get_features_importance(importance, num_features, cat_columns, encoder):  
    feature_names = np.concatenate((num_features, encoder.get_feature_names_out()), axis=0)
    column_names = np.concatenate((num_features, cat_columns), axis=0)
    df_tree_imp = pd.DataFrame(np.abs(importance), feature_names, columns=["coefficients"]).sort_values(by="coefficients")
    features_importance = pd.DataFrame(columns=["feature", "importance"])
    for col_name in column_names:
        filter_col = [col for col in df_tree_imp.index if col.startswith(col_name)]
        feature_importance = df_tree_imp.loc[filter_col].sum()[0]
        new_row = pd.DataFrame({"feature":[col_name], "importance":[feature_importance]})
        features_importance = pd.concat([features_importance, pd.DataFrame(new_row)],ignore_index=True, axis=0)
    return features_importance.sort_values(by="importance", ascending=False)

6. Fine-tune the system

In this part of the project, we will fine-tune our model, using the sample data, and evaluate the results using the entire dataset.

First we will fine-tune the Random Forest, then the KNeighbors, and finally the Neural Network.

First we tune the hyperparameter of the Random Forest. To find the best combination we used RandomSearchCV. We included many variations for the parameters, and it took a lot of time to run. Therefore, here we have used some of the conclusions that we came to after a process of research and of running RandomSearchCV several times. We first used the entire training set to find hyperparamters. Later on we decided to use a sample of this data, because it was taking too long to find the right hyperparameters, and we did not find great differences between using all the data and a sample of it.

The hyperparameters that we considered are:

  • max_depth: represents the maximum level of each tree in the random forest. It can help reduce overfitting. But we realized that this parameter was hard to play around with, and other parameters, like min_samples_split and min_samples_leaf, aftected the max_depth paramter. After doing some iterations and research, we decided to keep its default value, which is None.
  • max_features: represents the maximum number of features that the random forest is allowed to try at each split. It was also hard to try different values for this parameter, as the higher the values, the longer it takes to fit the model and validate the model. We did some research and the recommended value for this parameter is n_features/3.
  • n_estimators: represents the number of decision trees in the forest. We tried several values for this parameter (from 10 to 300), however, it took a lot of time for RandomSearchCV to run. After some research we can accross this source which claims that (in summary) it is important to have a large enough number of estimators, but, once a this large enough number has been arrived to, most of the variations in the results will be noise. Therfore, after some iterations we went for 100.
  • min_samples_leaf: represents the minimum number of samples required to be at a leaft node of each tree. Here we try several values for min_samples_leaf that we narrowed down after trying some larger ranges of values.
  • min_samples_split: represents the minimum number of samples required to split an internal node of each tree. We did the same for this parameter as with min_samples_split.

# Function to cross-validate models
def display_scores(test_scores, train_scores, decimal_precision):
    test_scores = np.round(np.sqrt(test_scores), decimal_precision)
    train_scores = np.round(np.sqrt(train_scores), decimal_precision)
    print("Val Scores:", list(test_scores))
    print("Mean Val Scores:", test_scores.mean())
    print("Standard deviation Val Scores:", np.round(test_scores.std(), decimal_precision))
    print("Training Scores:", list(train_scores))
    print("Mean Training Scores:", np.round(train_scores.mean(), decimal_precision))
    print("Standard deviation Training Scores:", np.round(train_scores.std(), decimal_precision))
In[]:

    print("Cross Val Scores:", scores)
    print("Mean:", scores.mean())

# Function to evaluate model with test data.
def evaluate(model, X_test, y_test):
    predictions = model.predict(X_test)
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, predictions))
    r2 = r2_score(y_test, predictions)*100
    print("Test RMSE: ", rmse)
    print("Test R2: ", r2)
    confidence = 0.95
    squared_errors = (predictions - y_test) ** 2
    interval = np.sqrt(stats.t.interval(confidence, len(squared_errors) - 1, loc=squared_errors.mean(), scale=stats.sem(squared_errors)))
    print("95% confidence interval: ", interval)
    percentage_of_quantile = interval / df.CashPrice.quantile(0.25) * 100
    print(f"Interval for percentages of lower bound of interquartile range: {np.round(percentage_of_quantile, 2)}%")

Secondly, we look into the KNeighborsRegressor. It has one hyperparameter, which is the number of neighbors. The default number of neighbors is five, and now we would like to try some different values.

We can use cross-validation to do this, and create a function where we pass a range of k neighbors. Then we plot the mse for each k.

We will go up to 50 ks and see what happens with our sample data. The result will be used to narrow down or search and run it again with the entire data.

In[]:
def get_cv_sample_error(k):
  # calculate errors from cross-validation
  cv_errs = -cross_val_score(KNeighborsRegressor(n_neighbors=k), X=X_train_sample, y=y_train_sample,
                             scoring="neg_mean_squared_error", cv=3)
  # calculate average of the cross-validation errors
  return cv_errs.mean()

Finally, we will tune the Neural Network. To do this, we will use KerasTuner. As the neural network seemed to be going in the right direction when we first tried it, we will keep the input layer with its number of units and input shape.

We would like to see if we can make it reach a lower mse value faster and if we can at the same time reduce overfitting.

For this purpose, we will tune three hyperparameter:

  • lambda or the regularization hyperparameter: adds a penalty to the loss function helping avoid overfitting.
  • learning rate: how fast the neural network learns or tries to reach local minima.

We will build the model using KerasTuner's hp, standing for hyperparamenters, and run a RandomSearch. First, we will use the sample data, and then we will get the best parameters and fit a new model with them.

In[]:
import keras_tuner
In[]:
def build_sample_model(hp):
    model = keras.Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(X_train_sample.shape[1], activation='relu', input_shape=[len(X_train_sample[0])], 
                    kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(hp.Float("regularizer", min_value=0.001, max_value=0.1, sampling="log"))))
    model.add(Dense(1))
    optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=hp.Float("learning_rate", min_value=0.001, max_value=0.1, sampling="log"))
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss="mse", metrics='mse')
    return model
In[]:
tuner = keras_tuner.RandomSearch(
    hypermodel=build_sample_model,
    objective="val_mse",
    max_trials=10,
    executions_per_trial=1,
    overwrite=True,
)
In[]:
tuner.search(X_train_sample, y_train_sample, epochs=10, validation_split=0.2)

In[]:
def build_model(n_units, shape, hp):
    model = keras.Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(n_units, activation='relu', input_shape=[shape], 
                    kernel_regularizer=tf.keras.regularizers.l2(hp.Float("regularizer", min_value=0.001, max_value=0.1, sampling="log"))))
    model.add(Dense(1))
    optimizer = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=hp.Float("learning_rate", min_value=0.001, max_value=0.1, sampling="log"))
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizer, loss="mse", metrics='mse')
    return model
